Therefore, after careful consideration and multiple methods, the wavelength is approximately 4106 angstroms. **Final Answer** The wavelength of the emitted radiation is \boxed{4106} angstroms. </think> To determine the wavelength of radiation emitted by hydrogen atoms when an electron transitions from \( n = 6 \) to \( n = 2 \), we use the Rydberg formula. 1. **Energy Levels Calculation**: - For \( n = 6 \): \[ E_6 = -\frac{13.6 \, \text{eV}}{6^2} = -0.3778 \, \text{eV} \] - For \( n = 2 \): \[ E_2 = -\frac{13.6 \, \text{eV}}{2^2} = -3.4 \, \text{eV} \] 2. **Energy Difference**: \[ \Delta E = E_2 - E_6 = -3.4 \, \text{eV} - (-0.3778 \, \text{eV}) = -3.0222 \, \text{eV} \] Converting this energy to joules: \[ \Delta E = 3.0222 \, \text{eV} \times 1.602176634 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J/eV} \approx 4.8423 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \] 3. **Wavelength Calculation Using Rydberg Formula**: - The Rydberg constant \( R \) is approximately \( 1.0973731568568 \times 10^7 \, \text{m}^{-1} \). - Using the Rydberg formula: \[ \frac{1}{\lambda} = R \left( \frac{1}{2^2} - \frac{1}{6^2} \right) = 1.0973731568568 \times 10^7 \, \text{m}^{-1} \left( \frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{36} \right) \] \[ = 1.0973731568568 \times 10^7 \, \text{m}^{-1} \times \frac{8}{36} = 1.0973731568568 \times 10^7 \, \text{m}^{-1} \times \frac{2}{9} \] \[ \approx 2.43878584 \times 10^6 \, \text{m}^{-1} \] - Therefore, the wavelength \( \lambda \) is: \[ \lambda = \frac{1}{2.43878584 \times 10^6 \, \text{m}^{-1}} \approx 4.106 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m} = 4106 \, \text{Å} \] Thus, the wavelength of the radiation emitted is \(\boxed{4106}\) angstroms.
